snippet.textDisplay: I’m glad they had to use massive miniatures, the movies will age really well compared to using CGI. I’m still flabbergasted at what they accomplished with this trilogy. I don’t think any movie has matched what they did since. All the sets, miniatures and costumes they created. On top of all the clever filming techniques and CGI they used. There has been better CGI since but all of the effort they put into this trilogy to make it a living breathing world is unparalleled.
snippet.textOriginal: I’m glad they had to use massive miniatures, the movies will age really well compared to using CGI. I’m still flabbergasted at what they accomplished with this trilogy. snippet.textDisplay: This seems to be the disconnect between the LotR trilogy and the Hobbit trilogy -- they had more time and care to do all the practical elements and bigatures and such, and not as heavy of a digital pipeline to fall back for everything. Then with the Hobbit, they seemed to almost be flying by the seat of their pants, going "eh, we'll fix it in digital/post," and not enough time to really fix things. Some of the stuff in the Hobbit trilogy still looks very good, but a lot more seems to be bad CGI.
snippet.textOriginal: This seems to be the disconnect between the LotR trilogy and the Hobbit trilogy -- they had more time and care to do all the practical elements and bigatures and such, and not as heavy of a digital pipeline to fall back for everything. Then with the Hobbit, they seemed to almost be flying by the seat of their pants, going "eh, we'll fix it in digital/post," and not enough time to really fix things. Some of the stuff in the Hobbit trilogy still looks very good, but a lot more seems to be bad CGI.
